Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["", "ManipulateCaptionSection",ExpressionUUID->"76c36dab-637d-452d-b47e-15d4c8ba6efd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This Demonstration calculates recursively the two-point Taylor expansion \
(2pTE) of a function, which is a polynomial expansion around two reference \
points. This expansion is increasingly accurate as the number of steps ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath",ExpressionUUID->
  "7fe2a7bd-c19f-40a4-a176-0bb7629ad2d0"],
 " in the recursion progresses. This block shows two examples of the 2pTE \
applied to two different functions as the degree of the fitting polynomial \
increases: One is the expansion of the sine function at the points ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"-", "2"}], "\[Pi]"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath",
  ExpressionUUID->"0dfd92bf-56dd-40c2-a20e-b4d708528623"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"2", "\[Pi]"}], TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath",ExpressionUUID->
  "6df345be-dbfc-481d-aabf-6b6ed98ebeb8"],
 ", while the standard one-point Taylor expansion around ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["0", TraditionalForm]], "InlineMath",ExpressionUUID->
  "3f987317-86f6-4042-8858-9c66b7bf3fb2"],
 " is shown for comparison. The second example is the expansion of the \
reciprocal function ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
